* ''Col. Henry J. Hunt''
* ''Gen. Henry Knox''
* ''Maj. Samuel Ringgold''
* ''Gen. Royal T. Frank''  (Became Army small transport serving in Hawaii, sunk by Japanese submarine I-71, 28 January 1942){{sfn|Kube-McDowell|2009}}{{sfn|Burritt|1942}}{{sfn|Hackett|Kingsepp|2010}}
* ''Gen. Samuel M. Mills'' (transferred to U.S. Coast Guard 29 April 1922, named  USCGC ''Pequot'' (WARC-58) on 1 May 1922, served as a cable ship until decommissioned 5 December 1946){{sfn|Kube-McDowell|2009}}{{sfn|U.S. Coast Guard, Historian|''Pequot''}}
* ''Gen. E. O. C. Ord''
* ''Gen. John M. Schofield''{{sfn|Kube-McDowell|2009}}

Cable ships ''Cyrus W. Field'' and ''Joseph Henry'' were associated with mine cable work and next generation mine planter development that incorporated cable capability into the new ships.{{sfn|Jackson|2013}}{{sfn|Gardner}} ''Joseph Henry'' was taken into the Mine Planter Service. The ''Cyrus W. Field'' appears listed only in association with mine cable work and with the mine planters in archival records.{{sfn|U.S. National Archives and Records Administration}}

* ''Joseph Henry'' (Became Greek cable ship ''Thalis o Milisios'' now at the Maritime Museum at Faliro, Athens){{sfn|Jackson|2013}}
* ''Cyrus W. Field'' (Remained with Signal Corps doing mine and other cable work.)

===Mine Planters 1917 - 1919===
A year after the 1918 establishment of the Mine Planter Service the next generation of vessels specifically designed to plant and maintain the mines and cables composing the mine battery of those harbor defense systems was added to the  fleet.  A year later, 1920, saw a major reduction in Army and the transfer of six of these new ships to the [[U.S. Lighthouse Service]] and later [[U.S. Coast Guard]] service.

Six of these vessels became [[United States Lighthouse Service]] vessels and were then brought into the [[United States Coast Guard]] as seen in the link.

